{"source_key":"sha256-6ca5768fdcbdfa1b766c39f8973d7416","record_index":309,"record_hash":"sha256:f152b50f3bf43e669e57f291c35b684db9136006ffdd03edc08d3ae74279737b","timestamp":"2026-05-20T15:41:28.770Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"user","text":"<subagent_notification>\n{\"agent_path\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"status\":{\"completed\":\"**Findings**\\n\\n[P2] `TomlRefMetadata` is safer than the old side-effecting read path, but it’s too much code to live in `but-agentlog`. [environment.rs:384](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/environment.rs:384) reimplements a legacy `RefMetadata` backend plus TOML-to-workspace conversion that already exists in `but-meta`; this will drift. Best simplification: move a truly read-only/no-sync TOML metadata constructor or adapter into `but-meta`, then delete the local adapter from agentlog.\\n\\n[P2] `TomlRefMetadata::branch()` has a subtle semantic drift from the real legacy backend. [environment.rs:503](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/environment.rs:503) marks a found branch as default when its metadata equals `Branch::default()`, while the legacy backend marks “found branch with empty review metadata” as non-default. Track `found` separately from value equality.\\n\\n[P3] `environment_from_parts` tests look worth keeping. They’re a little structural, but they lock the best-effort contract directly: failed when nothing is available, partial when either side survives. That’s not dead scaffolding.\\n\\n[P3] Private DTO fields are an improvement. The crate still exposes the minimum cross-module types `gitmeta` needs for serialization, and `EnvironmentObservation` accessors keep the write path from reaching into internals. No cleanup needed there.\"}}\n</subagent_notification>","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T15:41:28.770Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"user"}}}